LocationManager - Interface in com.phunware.engagement.location
LocationManager provides access to nearby Geozones and allows you to perform actions like checking in to a location. You can also supply a LocationListener to be notified of location related events, such as the addition or removal of geo zones, or entry and exit events. To receive geo zone notifications when your Activity is in the foreground, used to perform actions like updating the application UI or displaying additional information, add a LocationListener via the LocationManager.addLocationListener method. Note that you must also remove the listener via LocationManager.removeLocationListener to avoid leaks. SelectionBuilder - Class in com.phunware.engagement.internal.utils
Helper for building selection clauses for SQLiteDatabase. This class provides a convenient frontend for working with SQL. Instead of composing statements manually using string concatenation, method calls are used to construct the statement one clause at a time. These methods can be chained together. If multiple where() statements are provided, they're combined using AND. Example: SelectionBuilder builder = new SelectionBuilder(); Cursor c = builder.table(FeedContract.Entry.TABLE_NAME) // String TABLE_NAME = "entry" .where(FeedContract.Entry._ID + "=?", id); // String _ID = "_ID" .query(db, projection, sortOrder) In this example, the table name and filters (WHERE clauses) are both explicitly specified via method call. SelectionBuilder takes care of issuing a "query" command to the database, and returns the resulting Cursor object. Inner JOINs can be accomplished using the mapToTable() function. The map() function can be used to create new columns based on arbitrary (SQL-based) criteria. In advanced usage, entire subqueries can be passed into the map() function. Advanced example: // String SESSIONS_JOIN_BLOCKS_ROOMS = "sessions " // + "LEFT OUTER JOIN blocks ON sessions.block_id=blocks.block_id " // + "LEFT OUTER JOIN rooms ON sessions.room_id=rooms.room_id"; // String Subquery.BLOCK_NUM_STARRED_SESSIONS = // "(SELECT COUNT(1) FROM " // + Tables.SESSIONS + " WHERE " + Qualified.SESSIONS_BLOCK_ID + "=" // + Qualified.BLOCKS_BLOCK_ID + " AND " + Qualified.SESSIONS_STARRED + "=1)"; String Subqery.BLOCK_SESSIONS_COUNT = Cursor c = builder.table(Tables.SESSIONS_JOIN_BLOCKS_ROOMS) .map(Blocks.NUM_STARRED_SESSIONS, Subquery.BLOCK_NUM_STARRED_SESSIONS) .mapToTable(Sessions._ID, Tables.SESSIONS) .mapToTable(Sessions.SESSION_ID, Tables.SESSIONS) .mapToTable(Sessions.BLOCK_ID, Tables.SESSIONS) .mapToTable(Sessions.ROOM_ID, Tables.SESSIONS) .where(Qualified.SESSIONS_BLOCK_ID + "=?", blockId); In this example, we have two different types of JOINs: a left outer join using a modified table name (since this class doesn't directly support these), and an inner join using the mapToTable() function. The map() function is used to insert a count based on specific criteria, executed as a sub-query. This class is not thread safe.

SQLiteDatabaseHelper - Interface in com.phunware.engagement.internal.database
A helper class to manage table creation and versioning. Each module of the SDK should implement it's own helper to manage tables in it's domain. When the helper is registered with the SQLiteDatabaseManager, it's SQLiteDatabaseHelper.onCreate or SQLiteDatabaseHelper.onUpgrade method will be called, as needed. A simple implementation might look like this: public class FooDatabaseHelper implements DatabaseHelper { private static final String TABLE_NAME = "foos"; private static final int VERSION = 2; private final DatabaseManager mDbManager; public FooDatabaseHelper(DatabaseManager dbManager) { mDbManager = dbManager; mDbManager.addDatabaseHelper(this); } @Override @NonNull String getName() { return TABLE_NAME; } @Override int getVersion() { return VERSION; } @Override public void onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db) { db.exec("CREATE TABLE Foos(_ID INTEGER AUTOINCREMENT PRIMARY KEY, Content TEXT);"); } @Override public void onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int fromVersion, int toVersion) { int version = fromVersion; switch (version) { case 1: db.exec("ALTER TABLE Foos ADD COLUMN(IsRead INTEGER default 0);"); version++; } if (version != toVersion) { // Something went wrong with the upgrade, so drop and recreate. db.exec("DROP TABLE Foos;"); onCreate(db); } } public Foo getFooById(long id) { SQLiteDatabase db = mDbManager.getReadableDatabase(); Cursor c = db.query(...); return convertToFoo(c); } }

where() - Method in class com.phunware.engagement.internal.utils.SelectionBuilder
Append the given selection clause to the internal state. Each clause is surrounded with parenthesis and combined using AND. In the most basic usage, simply provide a selection in SQL WHERE statement format. Example: .where("blog_posts.category = 'PROGRAMMING'); User input should never be directly supplied as as part of the selection statement. Instead, use positional parameters in your selection statement, then pass the user input in via the selectionArgs parameter. This prevents SQL escape characters in user input from causing unwanted side effects. (Failure to follow this convention may have security implications.) Positional parameters are specified using the '?' character. Example: .where("blog_posts.title contains ?, userSearchString);
